\b Clarification\

\b0 The prime source of the misunderstanding lies in the polysemy of \uc0\u331 \u596 \u769 , which in BL is simply a synonym for\
n\uc0\u603 \u769  'stick to', but which is also the ordinary YL word for 'look at', and by extension for 'pay attention to; set store by'. The confusion is compounded by the syllable ma\u32 \u770  in Sentence (8). In the BL's intention, ma\u32 \u770  is the general classifier for objects (BL m\'e0), in constituency with the numeral te~ (BL t\'ea) 'one'. The YL interprets it, however, as ma~ 'not' (BL m\'e2). Thus ma\u32 \u770  \u331 \u596 \u32 \u769 , instead of meaning '(something) is stuck', becomes 'is not paying attention to; does not care a fig for.'\
Although it is not necessary to assume any further punning to ensure the success of the joke, it is possible that the syllable te~ is also involved in the verbal play. It is intended by the BL to mean 'one', but it could have been understood as the verb te 'do/act' by the YL. Thus:\
(BL's intention)            t\'ea m\'e2 \uc0\u331 \u596 \u769  'one thing is stuck'\
(YL's interpretation)   te ma~ \uc0\u331 \u596 \u32 \u769  'acts as if he doesn't give a fig for'.}